---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import PageHeader from "../components/PageHeader.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="CapitalBench Scoring"
  description="How CapitalBench scores AI model portfolio returns, S&P 500 returns, Portfolio Minus S&P 500, and the maximum-possible-return benchmark used for overall results."
>
  <PageHeader
    eyebrow="Scoring"
    title="How Scores Work"
    summary="Each test records portfolio return, S&P 500 return, Portfolio Minus S&P 500, and a CapitalBench Score that scales the result against the highest-returning scored option in that window."
  />
  <section class="section doc-layout">
    <article class="doc-body">
      <h2>Single-Test Result</h2>
      <p>
        Each model gets one saved portfolio for a test, and that portfolio is what appears on the public scoreboard.
        For a completed test, CapitalBench reports the raw portfolio return, the S&amp;P 500 return over the same
        close-to-close window, Portfolio Minus S&amp;P 500, and regret versus the highest-returning scored option.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Single-pick return: selected option ending price divided by starting price, minus one.</li>
        <li>Portfolio return: weighted sum of holding returns, using the submitted allocation percentages.</li>
        <li>Portfolio Minus S&P 500: portfolio return minus S&P 500 return.</li>
        <li>Maximum possible return: the highest realized return among scored options in the saved universe.</li>
        <li>Regret: maximum possible return minus the model's return, when full asset-list prices exist.</li>
        <li>Cash comparison: whether the model's return beats a cash return.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>CapitalBench Score</h2>
      <p>
        CapitalBench Score is the primary cumulative benchmark score. It asks how much of the best available return in
        each completed test a model captured. A score of 100 for a test means the model matched the highest-returning
        scored option in that same window. The S&amp;P 500 can also be plotted on this scale as a benchmark reference.
      </p>
      <p>
        The maximum possible return is a hindsight ceiling, not a model portfolio and not an investable recommendation.
        It exists to normalize different market windows: a one-week test where the best asset rises 2% and another
        where the best asset rises 12% can be compared on the same 0-to-100 scale.
      </p>

      <h2>Price Inputs</h2>
      <p>
        Starting and ending prices come from the test rules. Starting prices may be published while a test is pending.
        Ending prices and final returns are withheld until the test period is over and the scoring job has produced the
        result files.
      </p>
      <div class="formula-grid">
        <div>
          <span>Single-pick return</span>
          <code>(ending_price / starting_price) - 1</code>
        </div>
        <div>
          <span>Portfolio return</span>
          <code>sum(weight * option_return)</code>
        </div>
        <div>
          <span>Portfolio Minus S&amp;P 500</span>
          <code>portfolio_return - sp500_return</code>
        </div>
        <div>
          <span>Max possible return</span>
          <code>max(scored_universe_returns)</code>
        </div>
        <div>
          <span>CapitalBench Score</span>
          <code>100 * portfolio_return / max_possible_return</code>
        </div>
        <div>
          <span>Regret</span>
          <code>max_possible_return - portfolio_return</code>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>Overall Results</h2>
      <p>
        Overall results keep weekly and monthly tracks separate. For each completed test, CapitalBench computes the
        model's CapitalBench Score using that test's maximum possible return. The overall score is the average of those
        per-test scores across completed tests where the model actually participated.
      </p>
      <p>
        The overall view also shows average raw return and S&amp;P 500 context, but those are supporting context. The
        headline benchmark score is not a hidden weighting system, and it does not merge weekly tests with monthly
        tests or public picks with consistency checks.
      </p>

      <h2>Consistency Tests</h2>
      <p>
        Consistency tests summarize repeated calls with the same saved test input. They measure whether a model tends to
        make the same pick under identical conditions.
      </p>
      <p>
        These repeated-call checks are not mixed into the main scoreboard because the public contest uses one saved
        portfolio per model.
      </p>

      <h2>Pending Tests</h2>
      <p>
        Pending tests can show model portfolios, confidence values, rationale summaries, starting prices, and proof hashes.
        After at least one interim price snapshot exists, a test page may also show interim return tracking versus
        S&amp;P 500. That chart is explicitly provisional and separate from the final scoreboard. CapitalBench Score,
        rank, regret, maximum possible return, and final return versus S&amp;P 500 remain withheld until ending prices are
        present and the scorer publishes the result files.
      </p>
    </article>
    <aside class="side-panel">
      <strong>Main score</strong>
      <p>
        CapitalBench Score is normalized to the highest-returning scored option in each completed window. Raw return
        and S&amp;P 500 comparison remain visible as context.
      </p>
    </aside>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
